  "text": "An elevated LDL-C level is an established risk factor for CVD in people with diabetes. However, LDL-C levels do not reflect all aspects of diabetic dyslipidemia, which is characterized by an elevation in TG levels and low levels of HDL-C. Measuring plasma apolipoprotein B100 (ApoB100) concentrations may improve the definition of risk. Only one ApoB100 molecule is present on each LDL, intermediate-density lipoprotein, and very lowdensity lipoprotein (VLDL) particle. Thus, the concentration of ApoB100 can reflect the combined molecular concentrations of these atherogenic particle classes [CITATION_1] .",
